<html>
	<head>
		<meta name="keywords" content="Fit functions to measurement data">
		<title>Fit functions to measurement data</title>
		<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="normal.css">
	</head>
	<body>
		<h1>Fit functions to measurement data</h1>
		<img src="img/FitForm.png" align="left" hspace="20" vspace="10" />

		<p>In this dialogbox you can fit functions to measurement data.</p>


			
		<h3>Top Toolbar</h3>
		<p>
			In the two dropdown lists you can choose which function to fit to which data, if you have defined multiple functions or data.
		</p>
		<p>
			Next, with the <img alt="Algorithm" style="vertical-align:middle" src="img/Icons.MenuLayersLayerPropertiesIcon.png" /> dropdown button you can choose
			the fitting algorithm. There are two algorithms implemented, <b>Levenberg-Marquardt</b> and <b>Nelder & Mead</b>.
			The Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm is faster if your function provides <a href="FunctionForm.html#derivativeinfo">derivative information</a>.
			If you omit the derivative information, the algorithm computes numerical derivatives. The other algorithm does not use derivative
			information.  For more information about those algorithms please consult the book <em>Numerical Recipes in C</em>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Finally, you can choose how often to update the function views in your plots. If you have a function that evaluates very slowly, you might want to set this option to
			<img src="img/Icons.Progress.png" alt="Show No Progress" style="vertical-align:middle" /> <b>Show No Progress</b>. Otherwise you can keep this option at 
			<img src="img/Icons.Moderate.Progress.png" alt="Show No Progress" style="vertical-align:middle" /> <b>Show Moderate Progress</b>, this way FPlot will update the
			views every 5 seconds, or you can change this option to 
			<img src="img/Icons.Slow.Progress.png" alt="Show Full Progress" style="vertical-align:middle" /> <b>Show Full Progress</b>, so FPlot will update all views after every
			fitting step.
		</p>
		
		<h3>Bottom Toolbars</h3>
		<p>
			Here the Chisquare
			<img alt="Chisquare" src="img/Icons.Chisquare.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> and the
			<img alt="Q" src="img/Icons.Q.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> (Goodness of fit) values 
			of the fit are displayed. The value of <em>Q</em> 
			is the incomplete gamma function <img alt="Q((N-2)/2, chisquare/2)" style="vertical-align:middle" src="img/gammq.Transparent.png" />where 
			<em>N</em> is the number of data points and <em>M</em> is the number of parameters fitted for (An exact explanation of the <em>Q</em> 
			function can be found in the book <em>Numerical Recipes in C</em>). 
			The value <img alt="N of f" src="img/Icons.NOfF.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> denotes the number of function evaluations so far.
		</p>
		<p>
			The <img alt="Start" src="img/Icons.Run.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> button starts or continues the fit.<br />
			The <img alt="Pause" src="img/Icon.Pause.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> button interrupts a fit.<br />
			The <img alt="Close" src="img/Images.ImageStrip.CloseButton.Hot.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> button closes the window.<br />
			The <img alt="Undo" src="img/Icons.MenuEditUndoIcon.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> and 
				<img alt="Redo" src="img/Icons.MenuEditRedoIcon.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> buttons undo or redo the last fit step.<br />
			The <img alt="Help" src="img/Icons.MenuHelpHelpTopicsIcon.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> button shows this text.<br />
			The <img alt="Covariance Matrix" src="img/Icons.PlusMinus.png" style="vertical-align:middle" /> button shows the covariance matrix of the fit.
		</p>
		
		<h3>Parameters Grid</h3>
		<p>
			In this grid you can view and edit the function parameters. In the checkboxes on the left you select which parameters to fit for. You can edit
			the parameters for an initial guess. On the right, the errors are displayed. This errors correspond to a 68% confidence interval,
			e.g. they are simply the square-roots of the diagonal elements of the covariance matrix of the fit.
		</p>
	</body>
</html>
